communications.subject: Louisiana Public Records Law Request: Louisiana State Employees (2019 - 2022)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Louisiana Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Monthly electronic listings of all employees of the Louisiana Executive Branch from January 1, 2019 to the present. Specifically, I am seeking electronic listings of all individuals employed within the offices of the Governor and Lieutenant Governor and all state agencies, commissions, and departments for each month from January 1, 2019 to May 31, 2022.

For each month, I’m seeking a spreadsheet, database, or delimited text file(s) — not paper records or a PDF created from data — with the following fields for each employee: full legal name, unique employee identification code, title, department or agency, race, gender, full-time/part-time status, location, hire date, termination date, civil service status, and gross annual salary. If you cannot produce any of these fields, please let me know and generate only the available variables.

If these data are not available at monthly intervals, please produce the datasets at the most frequent interval possible. For example, if the data is not available monthly, please produce the data at quarterly intervals.

In addition, please include any lookup tables that may be needed to interpret the data. For example, if departments are listed with codes linked to a separate table, I will be happy to join the records myself, rather than require your staff to do so.

I am comfortable working with large data sets and can receive the records in a variety of formats (.dbf, .csv, .mdb, etc).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Goehring

The Division of Administration received your June 7, 2022 email; however, additional clarification is required.


·         For each employee, you requested their ”title”. Are you referring to their job title?

·         For each employee, you requested their “location”. Are you referring to their work location? If so, please be advised that each employee’s work address is not listed on any report. The parish of the employee’s work location can be provided instead.

·         For each employee, you requested their “gross annual salary”. Are you referring to their annual salary or to their gross wages?

Once we receive your clarification, we can begin processing your request.


Thank you.


Public Records Requests

communications.communication:
Mr. Goehring,

While the Office of State Uniform Payroll (OSUP) continues processing its reports, the Division would like to provide you with another document that is in our possession.

The attached excel spreadsheet was prepared by the Department of State Civil Service. It includes salary information for all executive branch employees paid through OSUP as well as employees of public universities who are paid through other systems. OSUP does not process payroll for public universities, and therefore, any reporting prepared by OSUP does not include those employees. In short, the attached document is more comprehensive than what OSUP and the Division of Administration can provide.

Because this document was prepared by the Department of State Civil Service, any questions regarding its contents should be directed to them.

If this document satisfies your request, please respond accordingly so that OSUP can remove your report out of its queue in order to facilitate their other reporting requirements. Otherwise, OSUP’s report will be provided to you when it is available. At this time, we still anticipate that a response will be provided to you by January 13, 2023.



Thank you.

Public Records Requests

Division of Administration

State of Louisiana

Email: doapublicrecords@la.gov<mailto:doapublicrecords@la.gov>

communications.communication:
Mr. Goehring:

Your June 7, 2022 public records request was received by the Division of Administration on that same date. In response to your public records request, the Office of State Uniform Payroll has produced several spreadsheets, which can be accessed using the following DropBox link:

https://www.dropbox.com/sh/jhn4dw20nhs8he5/AAC7fSDwEij-wSXtdvcsTNo5a?dl=0

The information provided is for employees of executive branch agencies paid through the LaGov HCM payroll system.  This does not include higher education or agencies in the legislative and judicial branches of government.

The worksheets are sorted by Agency Number. The Agency Name Reference workbook contains a mapping of personnel area (PA) number (agency) to personnel area text (agency name). The first three (3) characters in the name represent the department.

There may be employees on the Demographic worksheets and not on the Race_Gender_Work Parish worksheets. This is because the position does not have a work parish specified and thus they are excluded from the report used to gather this information.

With this production, the Division of Administration considers your public records request satisfied and will close its file.

Thank you for your patience.

Public Records Requests
Division of Administration
State of Louisiana
Email: doapublicrecords@la.gov<mailto:doapublicrecords@la.gov>

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Phrack
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Files mentioning Phrack, an ezine written by and for hackers, first published November 17, 1985. During its first 10 years of publication, Phrack has been largely associated with the telecommunications fraud, providing material for phreakers and informing about arrests in this community through the Phrack World News feature articles. The 24th issue of Phrack, released February 1989, included a document relating to the workings of Enhanced 911 emergency response systems. This document, copied from a BellSouth computer, played a major part in a series of Secret Service raids called Operation Sundevil and featured in Bruce Sterling's book The Hacker Crackdown.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best

Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@ic.fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 134 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 523 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,335 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 1,875 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
Record/Information Dissemination Section (RIDS) FBI-Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive, Winchester, VA 22602-4843
Direct: (540) 868-4593
Fax: (540) 868-4391
Questions E-mail: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

communications.subject: Iowa Open Records Law Request: Iowa Freedom of Information Act. Request: Iowa Freedom of Information Act. Request: Pepsi and Coke (University of Iowa)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the { Iowa  Freedom of Information Act }, I hereby request the following records:

communications.subject: Acknowledgment of your public records request
communications.communication:
Kayla,

The University of Iowa Office of the President received your faxed request, copy attached, and forwarded it to my office to process. Your message indicates the request was originally submitted on January 23, 2023, but we checked our records, and we did not receive your request.

We will send this request to our procurement team for a response. We will get back to you if there are any fees involved with compiling responsive records, in accordance with our fee schedule<https://transparency.uiowa.edu/faqs/public-records-fee-schedule>.

Please note that suppliers may need to be notified of this request for their contract and be given the opportunity to assert if any of the information contained in their contract is a trade secret that should be redacted and exempted from disclosure. As additional information, please note that the Iowa Court of Appeals (Sysco v U of Iowa (2016)<https://www.iowacourts.gov/media/documents/150999_3FDEA880C59FF.pdf> has recently held that pricing and other financial information may be a trade secret.

We will begin compiling the records you requested, but please be aware that due to the notification process mentioned above, there may be a delay in fulfilling your request. We will provide the records as soon as possible.


Aubree Johnson
Office of Transparency
The University of Iowa
351 Plaza Centre One
Iowa City, IA 52242
public-records@uiowa.edu<mailto:public-records@uiowa.edu>

title: FOIL: Procedures for handling removal of school officers by NYSED Commissioner (Sole Supervisory District Of Cattaraugus-allegany-erie-wyoming Counties And Boces)

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: FOIL: Procedures for handling removal of school officers by NYSED Commissioner (Sole Supervisory District Of Cattaraugus-allegany-erie-wyoming Counties And Boces)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

All materials related to processes that would need to take place if the Commissioner of Education of the State of New York removes one, multiple or all board members, school officers or superintendents from a school district under the jurisdiction of  your sole supervisory district (your organization). Specifically, I request any and all materials including, but not limited to:

1) Policies, procedures, and protocols for responding to the removal of board members, school officers or superintendents, including but not limited to filling vacancies and ensuring continuity of school district operations.

2) Records of any past instances where the Commissioner of Education has removed board members, school officers or superintendents from school districts under the jurisdiction of your sole supervisory district (your organization) and the actions taken by the sole supervisory district (your organization) or NYSED in response.

3) Any other records or materials relevant to the processes that would need to take place if the Commissioner of Education removes one, multiple or all board members, school officers or superintendents from a school district under the jurisdiction of the sole supervisory district (your organization).

Please provide any records or materials that are responsive to this request, regardless of format or medium. If some records are not subject to disclosure, please provide the reasons for the denial of access.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jackson Parker

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: OIS - Firearms Discharges
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) Incident-level data on Elizabeth (NJ) Police Department officers’ drawing their weapons/firearms in the course of their duty: I request data from years 2000 to 2020, including the time, date, and street address (e.g. 123 Main St) for all incidents where an officer drew their weapon/firearm;
2) Incident-level data on the Elizabeth (NJ) Police Department officers’ discharging their weapons/firearms in the course of their duty: I request data from years 2000 to 2020, including the time, date, and street address (e.g. 123 Main St) for all incidents where an officer discharged their firearm;
3) If incident-level data on the Elizabeth (NJ) Police Department officers’ discharging their firearms in the course of duty from years 2000 to 2020 inclusive is available, I also request associated data on whether the shootings by the officers were lethal (i.e. suspects or civilians died as a result of gunshots from officers’ weapons) or were non-lethal (i.e. suspects or civilians were shot but did not die); and
4) Demographic data on the officers and suspects or civilians involved in each incident of Elizabeth (NJ) Police Department officers drawing, discharging, and/or striking (lethal and non-lethal) of suspects or civilians.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Michael Owens

communications.subject: OPRA Request (#352) - Firearm Discharges
communications.communication:
Good afternoon Mr. Owens:

This email is in response to your request for public records dated March 7, 2023, to the City Clerk of the City of Elizabeth pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, N.J.S.A. 47:1A-1 et seq. (OPRA).



You sought the following records:

  1.  Incident-level data on Elizabeth (NJ) Police Department [EPD] officers’ drawing their weapons/firearms in the course of their duty […] from years 2000 to 2020, including the time, date, and street address (e.g. 123 Main St) for all incidents where an officer drew their weapon/firearm;
  2.  Incident-level data on [EPD] officers’ discharging their weapons/firearms in the course of their duty […] from years 2000 to 2020, including the time, date, and street address (e.g. 123 Main St) for all incidents where an officer discharged their firearm;
  3.  If incident-level data on the [EPD] officers’ discharging their firearms in the course of their duty from years 2000 to 2020 inclusive is available, [you requested] associated data on whether the shootings by the officers were lethal (i.e. suspects or civilians died as a result of gunshots’ from officers’ weapons) or non-lethal (i.e. suspects or civilians were shot but did not die); and
  4.  Demographic data on the officers and suspects or civilians involved in each incident of [EPD] officers drawing, discharging, and/or striking (lethal and non-lethal) of suspects or civilians.

Regarding all four of your data requests, please be advised that no responsive records exist from 2000-2006. From 2007 until May 2015, all use of force reports with the requested information are stored in scanned PDF form. There is no way to collate the data besides recording it one-by-one, which requires the custodian to conduct research and create a new record, which she is not required to do under OPRA. From May 2015 to September 2020, the use of force reports have been archived as the EPD no longer uses the system the reports were originally stored in. At this time, we are still determining if the data for these records can be collated into easily generated data. Please allow the City’s custodian additional time of seven (7) business days to investigate further.

For the year 2020, all of the data requested for 2020 to present is readily available on the New Jersey Attorney General’s website (https://www.njoag.gov/force/). Once you follow the link, you must scroll down and click “Access Use of Force Dashboard”. From there, you are able to search for the EPD and the requested types of force and demographics and find the records you are searching for. EPD inputs this information directly to the State, so records for 2020 will be identical to those found on the State dashboard.


Thank you for your continued patience, I will reach back out with the status of the 2007-May 2015 data shortly.


All the best,


Samantha J. Castrelos, Esq.
Special Counsel
City of Elizabeth, Law Department
50 Winfield Scott Plaza, Room 201
Elizabeth, New Jersey 07201
(908) 820-4009

communications.subject: RE: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request #352
communications.communication:
Thank you for the message, Ms. Castrelos. It's very helpful.

Regarding the use of force reports from 2007 though mid-2015 that are are only available via PDF, may I request copies of the PDFs of the reports? That would meet my initial request that whatever I receive be "filled electronically, by e-mail attachment." It also would mean that there'd be no need for the custodian to do any research, and there'd be no need for a new record to be created create collation. The same would be true if I the reports from mid-May 2015 through 2019 were PDFs, too.

Again, thank you.

communications.subject: Re: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request #352
communications.communication:
Hi Michael,
So it looks like we are able to send over scanned copies of use of force reports. I actually misspoke in my last email when I said they were stored as scanned PDFs. They are actually stored as hard copies but we can scan and send over. However we still need to review each report as sometimes the civilians are minors so their identities will need to be redacted. Is there a time frame in which you need to receive all records by? We can begin this process but it does take some time for review and we can send over on a rolling basis if there is no rush. Please advise.
Thank you,
Samantha

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Jon Burge
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to or mentioning Jon Graham Burge (December 20, 1947 – September 19, 2018), a former Chicago Police Department detective and commander who was accused of torturing more than 200 criminal suspects between 1972 and 1991. In 2008, Patrick Fitzgerald, United States Attorney for Northern Illinois, charged Burge with obstruction of justice and perjury in relation to testimony in a 1989 civil suit against him for damages for alleged torture. Burge was convicted on all counts on June 28, 2010, and sentenced to four-and-one-half years in federal prison on January 21, 2011. He was released in October 2014.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1417710-000
communications.communication:
Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@ic.fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 134 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 523 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,335 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 1,875 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
Record/Information Dissemination Section (RIDS) FBI-Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive, Winchester, VA 22602-4843
Direct: (540) 868-4593
Fax: (540) 868-4391
Questions E-mail: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Request for Probation Departments: Employee Salaries and Use of Force Training Documents (Westchester County Department Of Probation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to request the following information:

A complete list of all employees, their job titles, and their annual salary for the last Three years (2020 and 2023).

Please provide all training documents related to the use of force within the agency, including but not limited to manuals, protocols, guidelines, and any related memos or communications.
I am making this FOIA request with any and all agencies that may have the requested information.

The purpose of this request is to gather information that will aid in a research project examining agency practices related to the use of force. The information requested will be used to assess the extent to which agency training on the use of force has been effective. This research project is being conducted as part of a larger effort to promote greater accountability and transparency within law enforcement agencies.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jordan

communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@ic.fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 138 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 571 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,289 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 1,649 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
Record/Information Dissemination Section (RIDS) FBI-Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive, Winchester, VA 22602-4843
Direct: (540) 868-4593
Fax: (540) 868-4391
Questions E-mail: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Olympia School District – Request for a complete electronic copy of all Public Records Requests received by the District including District Responses for the years 2010 - 2021
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

I request a complete electronic copy of all Public Records Requests received by Olympia School District and a complete electronic copy of the District's Responses to these Public Records Requests for the time period January 1, 2010 through November 4, 2021.

In the event the District chooses to provide these records in installments over time I request the records to be produced in reverse chronological order - from the most recent records to the earliest.

If this request is denied in whole or part, I ask that you justify all deletions by reference to specific exemptions of the PRA. I also request a detailed contemporaneous log to be provided for any document withheld or redacted.

For each responsive record the District contends is exempt from public disclosure, in whole or in part, please specifically identify the record by subject, title, author, custodian and date, and state how a specific statutory exemption applies to each record as required by RCW 42.56.210(3) and Rental Housing Ass'n v. Des Moines, 165 Wn.2d 525, 199 P.3d 393 (2009).

I request electronic production of all electronic records in the original NATIVE electronic format for each record. 

I request for these public records to be produced by public (no password) e-mail attachment or link. If electronic attachment or link is not possible, an alternative would be to produce responsive records via USB DRIVE or DATA CD-ROM.

THIS REQUEST IS NOT BEING MADE FOR COMMERCIAL PURPOSES.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

PRA Audit

communications.communication:
Hello Ms. Crawford,

Thank you for your email. 

To answer your question regarding excluding public records requests and responsive records made by parents/guardians about their own students. We would agree to exclude records requests made by parents/guardians about their students for their student’s grades and educational file only.

Presumably, virtually an entire students educational file would be exempt from any public records request. 

You reference records from 2012 to 2016 that are paper that need to be scanned to .pdf but also claim the District follows the State of Washington Core Retention Schedule and purges records accordingly.

 If the District follows the Core schedule it would retain no records from 2012 to 2016. Please explain. 

Also please produce records in reverse chronological order, with the newest records to be produced first. 

Thank you.

communications.communication:
Muckrock requester,

We sent the attached letter to you mid July answering your previous
questions, please confirm that you received it.  Our fee schedule was
detailed to you in our acknowledgement letter and is as follows:

It is policy of the District, to provide paper records for review and to
charge the following for any copies that are requested:

·       $.15 per page for *paper* letter and legal sized documents if more
than 25 pages are provided;

·       $.10 per page for more than 25 pages for *electronic documents
transferred from paper* originals;

·       $.05 per page for every 4 pages of *electronic original documents*
for more than 25 pages.

The charges for the latest installment we notified you about ($82.79),
are calculated at $.05 per page for every 4 pages of electronic original
documents more than 25 pages.

We are producing records in the same way original requests were produced.

Please let me know if you have any further questions.

communications.communication:
Muckrock requester:

Below is the text of the response sent to you in a letter via email last
month mid July.  I also resent the letter via email to you on August 9,
2022.

The $82.79 fee is for the 8th installment of records which is electronic
records billed at $.0125 per page or $.05 per 4 pages as detailed in our
fee schedule provided to you in our letter dated November 15, 2021:
*"it is the policy of the District to charge the following for electronic
copies that are requested:  $.10 per page for electronic documents
transferred from paper originals and $.05 per page for every 4 pages of
electronic original documents."*

Since the requests and records being provided to you in installments #1-7,
and yet-to-be provided pending payment installment #8, are electronic PDFs,
they are billed at the fee detailed above for electronic original documents.

July 19, 2022

PRA Audit

*Muckrock*

120981-94672018@requests.muckrock.com


Dear MuckRock Requester,


Thank you for your email.  We received your email requesting clarification
about our methodology in responding to your public records request.


As we detailed to you in a previous communication, many of our public
records requests concern students and staff. We have approximately 136
public records requests that are responsive to your request that require 3rd
party notification related to hundreds of people.
                                           2020-2021- 28 requests require 3
rd party notification

                                                          2018-2019 – 13
requests require 3rd party notification

                                                          2012-2017 – 95
requests require 3rd party notification



·       With our last installment, we have provided to you, in reverse
chronological order, all requests for records covering 2012-2021 that do
not require 3rd party notification.  Next we will be providing non-exempt
records responsive to those requests.

·       After those installments, we will move on to the requests that
require 3rd party notification, allowing time for affected parties to seek
injunctions if they so choose.  Absent injunctions, we will then provide
non-exempt records responsive to those requests.


Most of our responsive records are available electronically, but many from
2012 – 2017 are in paper form and will need to be scanned into PDFs.
Emails are printed and then scanned to PDF for production.  We are making
steady progress in fulfilling your request but are unable to give an exact
date when the request will be completed in full.


Please let us know if you have any other questions.


Sincerely,




Diana S. Crawford

Public Disclosure Officer

Diana

communications.subject: Tennessee Public Records Act Request: Records related to Audrey Hale, who shot up Covenant Presbyterian Church/The Covenant School in Nashville, Tennessee on or about March 27, 2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Tennessee Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

scanned copy on electronic media of sufficient resolution so all text is easily legible of the following:
from the "Inventory of Seized Property," presumably from the Metropolitan Police Department of Nashville,  dated 3-27-23, complaint #2023-01831907
Items #
2  7 journals
3  1 journal
6  note "new song"
8  2 journals
9  suicide note
11  3 folders, 19(?) journals (school shootings, firearms courses)
23   [redacted] (if this is an object, several photos that clearly depict what it is, and that reveal all features)
29  notes written by Audrey
31  writings / 1 journal
32  memoir
43  memoir

scanned copy on electronic media of sufficient resolution so all text is easily legible of:
what has been referred to as the "manifesto" by Police Chief John Drake, and also referenced by the Chief in the press conference:
all other written materials found in the vehicle or elsewhere, pertaining to the March 27 shooting, including maps, surveillance details, details how the attack(s) were going to be carried out, etc
all "writings that pertain to this day [the day of the shooting]" (quote from Chief Drake)
all writings that include the "threat assessment" and "another location that was mentioned" (quote from Chief Drake)

All phone texts, emails, or other formats of communication within the last year to or from Audrey Hale's devices/accounts

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kent Hoover, a citizen of Tennessee, in coordination with David Treibs.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Untitled
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all records pertaining to the AFOSI investigation into the April 2, 1997 death of USAF Captain Craig Button, including the name and rank of his flight trainer at the time of his death and the names of the other flight trainers at the Davis-Monthan Air Force Base during the duration of Button's time there;  plus flight records and flight logs for of all Button's missions in 1997, as well as those of pilot Amy Lynn Svoboda through May of 1997.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Greg Schwartz

Your initial Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request was received by this
office on 10 August 2022. Your request was assigned tracking number AF
2022-05473-F. 

 

To ensure fairness to all families, we are required to process all FOIA
requests on a "first in, first out" basis, in accordance with Federal Law,
DoD and Air Force Instructions.  Many of these requests involve the loss of
loved ones, sexual assaults and other sensitive matters.  As such, requests
could take a minimum of 6 months to substantially longer to complete based
upon the number and complexity of your case or the cases that precede it or
other mitigating circumstances.

 

You may also contact the Air Force FOIA Public Liaison Officer, Ms. Adriane

communications.subject: Request Acknowledgement - AF 2023-02755-F
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Schwartz, 
This is to acknowledge receipt of referral of information from Air Force Office of Special Investigation (AFOSI) your 10 August 2023, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request for "any and all records pertaining to the AFOSI investigation into the April 2, 1997 death of USAF Captain, including the name and rank of his flight trainer at the time of his death and the names of the other flight trainers at the Davis-Monthan Air Force Base during the duration of Button's time there; plus flight records and flight logs for of all Button's missions in 1997, as well as those of pilot Amy Lynn Svoboda through May of 1997. 
During processing of your initial request AFOSI located documents which fall under the purview of the Headquarters Air Force and subsequently referred those records to our office for processing and response to you. 
Based on our initial review, we believe we cannot process your request within the statutory 20 workdays because our organization has a significant number of pending FOIA requests.  To ensure all requesters are properly served in the order their requests were received, we have instituted multitrack processing of requests.  Based on the information you provided, we have placed your request in the complex track. 
We have assigned number 2022-05601-F to identify your request; should you need to contact us about your request.  Please direct your questions to Mr. Jonathan Staeblein at jonathan.staeblein@us.af.mil or SAF.AA.HAF.FOIA.Workflow@us.af.mil and use this assigned number to assist us in responding more promptly. 
We will strive to provide an update between 90 and 120 days.  Our policy is to process requests within their respective tracks in the order in which they were received in accordance with 32 CFR, Part 286.8.  We will notify you in writing if additional processing time is required.  We do process each FOIA request as quickly as possible, however delayed responses can be expected. 
Very Respectfully, 
JONATHAN STAEBLEIN, GS-12, DAF 
SAF/AAII (FOIA) 
Office of the Secretary of the Air Force 
1000 Air Force Pentagon 
Washington, DC 20330-1000

communications.subject: Your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Request 2023-02855-F
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Schwartz, 
This responds to your 01-Sep-22 FOIA request 2023-02855-F received on 20-Mar-23, which seeks the following: 
 Any and all records pertaining to the AFOSI investigation into the April 2, 1997 death of USAF Captain Craig Button,including the name and rank of his flight trainer at the time of his death and the names of the other flight trainers at theDavis-Monthan Air Force Base during the duration of Button's time there; plus flight records and flight logs for of allButton's missions in 1997, as well as those of pilot Amy Lynn Svoboda through May of 1997. 
We reviewed 45 pages for release anddetermined they are granted in part because FOIA Exemptions 6 permit the redaction of information that should be withheld and protected in accordancewith 5 U.S.C. §552a.  Our review included consideration of the “Foreseeable Harm Standard.” The records areattached. If you disagree and interpret thisresponse as an adverse action, you may write to the Secretary of the Air Force,Through: 47 CS FOIA Office 350 Mitchell Blvd. Bldg. 348 Laughlin AFB, TX 78843 within 90calendar days from the date of this letter. Include in the appeal your reasons for reconsideration and attach acopy of this letter. You may also submit your appeal online at the Air Force’sPublic Access Link: https://efoia.cce.af.mil/ (https://efoia.cce.af.mil/) .You may contact the Air Force FOIAPublic Liaison Officer, Mr. Robert E. Bivins, concerning this final response at AirForce FOIA Public Liaison Office, 1800 Air Force Pentagon, Washington, DC20330-1800 or 
DAF.FOIA@us.af.mil or(703) 614-8500. You may also seek dispute resolution services from the Officeof Government Information Services and can find information on this Office at (mailto:DAF.FOIA@us.af.mil) https://www.archives.gov/ogis/mediation-program/request-assistance. (https://www.archives.gov/ogis/mediation-program/request-assistance) Using thedispute resolution services, will not affect your appeal rights. 
The FOIA Office provides for the collectionof fees based on the costs of processing a FOIA request and your feecategory.  In this case, we assessed nofees for processing this request. Direct questions to 47CS.SCXK.FOIA@us.af.mil or call 830-298-9298 andreference the above FOIA case number. Sincerely, //SIGNED// 
Gustavo Cantu, SSgt, USAF 
Freedom of Information Act Manager Attachment:

communications.subject: Michigan Freedom of Information Act Request: Untitled
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Michigan Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to MCL 780.993(3), an indigent defense system is required to "submit an annual plan" that "specifically address how the minimum standards established by the MIDC under this act will be met and must include a cost analysis for meeting those minimum standards." In addition, "[w]ithin 180 days after receiving funds from the MIDC" an "an indigent criminal defense system shall comply with the terms of the grant in bringing its system into compliance with the minimum standards established by the MIDC for effective assistance of counsel[,]" subject to the "terms of a grant" which "may allow an indigent criminal defense system to exceed 180 days for compliance with a specific item needed to meet minimum standards if necessity is demonstrated in the indigent criminal defense system's compliance plan." MCL 780.993(11).

I am requesting the FY 22, 23, and 24 compliance plans and cost analysis, as well as any revisions or resubmissions of the the compliance plan for the Wayne County indigent defense system. In addition, I am requesting copies of the grants for FY 22, 23, and 24 for the Wayne County indigent defense system. 

I am also requesting any additional correspondence or materials regarding Wayne County's noncompliance with Standard 5, compliance with which was mandated by April 2022.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Annika Brigham

In accordance with the Michigan Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), MI LARA provides copies of its public records. Records which are exempt from disclosure by state or federal law will not be provided. 
 
 
The FOIA does not require governmental bodies to create new records or answer questions. A request must ask for records or information already in existence. A person has the right to subscribe to future issuance of public records that are created, issued or disseminated on a regular basis. 
 
Michigan LARA will respond within five business days to a request. If needed, the agency may issue a notice extending for up to 10 additional business days the time it has to respond to your request. 
You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you'll receive an email when your request has been completed.

communications.subject: FOIA Request :: R106941-030723
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

 
March 14, 2023 
RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of March 08, 2023, Reference # R106941-030723. 
Dear Requester: 
This notice responds to your March 08, 2023 request for records, received by the Michigan Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs (LARA).  LARA has processed your request under the provisions of the Michigan Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), 1976 PA 442, MCL 15.231 et seq. 
You requested the following, in summary: 
“To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Michigan Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records: 

Pursuant to MCL 780.993(3), an indigent defense system is required to "submit an annual plan" that "specifically address how the minimum standards established by the MIDC under this act will be met and must include a cost analysis for meeting those minimum standards." In addition, "[w]ithin 180 days after receiving funds from the MIDC" an "an indigent criminal defense system shall comply with the terms of the grant in bringing its system into compliance with the minimum standards established by the MIDC for effective assistance of counsel[,]" subject to the "terms of a grant" which "may allow an indigent criminal defense system to exceed 180 days for compliance with a specific item needed to meet minimum standards if necessity is demonstrated in the indigent criminal defense system's compliance plan." MCL 780.993(11). 

I am requesting the FY 22, 23, and 24 compliance plans and cost analysis, as well as any revisions or resubmissions of the the compliance plan for the Wayne County indigent defense system. In addition, I am requesting copies of the grants for FY 22, 23, and 24 for the Wayne County indigent defense system. 

I am also requesting any additional correspondence or materials regarding Wayne County's noncompliance with Standard 5, compliance with which was mandated by April 2022." 
Your request is granted. 
The estimated cost of continuing to process your request is $93.06. Please refer to the attached Detailed Itemization Form for a breakdown of the fees. Failure to charge would result in an unreasonably high cost to the Department in this particular instance because the employees must be taken away from pending work to process the request, and expend additional time to complete regularly assigned departmental work. 
Section 4(8) of the FOIA, MCL 15.234(8), provides that a public body may require a good-faith deposit of one-half of the estimated FOIA processing fee. Upon the FOIA Office’s receipt of a payment for one-half of the above-stated amount, the request will be processed within an estimated 15 business days. Further, upon completing the processing of the request, the Department will send notice of the balance due, the statutory basis for exemptions, if any, and the statutory remedial rights, if applicable. After receipt of the fee balance, copies of the records will be provided to you within five business days. To avoid processing delays, please only pay the amount shown on the invoice (half of the total estimated fees). 
Section 4(8) of the FOIA, MCL 15.234(8), provides that the time frame estimate is nonbinding upon the public body, but the public body shall provide the estimate in good faith and strive to be reasonably accurate and provide the records in a manner based on this state’s public policy set forth in section 1(2) of the FOIA, MCL 15.231(2), and the nature of the request in the particular instance. 
The invoice that contains the detailed itemization of fees is ready and available at the FOIA Center  . 
If you wish to discuss possible ways to reduce the costs, please contact us at . (mailto:larafoiainfo@michigan.gov) larafoiainfo@michigan.gov 
Payment can be submitted online or by mail – 
• To pay online, visit the following link: FOIA Payment Center . 
•To pay by check or money order (via mail), send the check or money order, made payable to the State of Michigan to P.O. Box 30004, Lansing, MI 48909. To ensure proper credit, please enclose a copy of the invoice included with this correspondence and include the FOIA request number on the check or money order. 
Please note that, if payment is not received within 48 calendar days after this notice is sent, your request may be considered as abandoned under MCL 15.234(14). 
If you have questions concerning this matter, please email us at . (mailto:larafoiainfo@michigan.gov) larafoiainfo@michigan.gov 
To review a copy of LARA’s written public summary, procedures, and guidelines, please visit . www.michigan.gov/larafoia 
Sincerely, Andrea Moua 
LARA FOIA Office

communications.subject: FOIA Request :: R106941-030723
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

 
May 09, 2023 
RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of 3/8/2023, Reference # R106941-030723. 
Dear Requester: 
The Michigan Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs (LARA) received your final payment. 
You requested the following, in summary: 
“To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Michigan Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records: 

Pursuant to MCL 780.993(3), an indigent defense system is required to "submit an annual plan" that "specifically address how the minimum standards established by the MIDC under this act will be met and must include a cost analysis for meeting those minimum standards." In addition, "[w]ithin 180 days after receiving funds from the MIDC" an "an indigent criminal defense system shall comply with the terms of the grant in bringing its system into compliance with the minimum standards established by the MIDC for effective assistance of counsel[,]" subject to the "terms of a grant" which "may allow an indigent criminal defense system to exceed 180 days for compliance with a specific item needed to meet minimum standards if necessity is demonstrated in the indigent criminal defense system's compliance plan." MCL 780.993(11). 

I am requesting the FY 22, 23, and 24 compliance plans and cost analysis, as well as any revisions or resubmissions of the the compliance plan for the Wayne County indigent defense system. In addition, I am requesting copies of the grants for FY 22, 23, and 24 for the Wayne County indigent defense system. 

I am also requesting any additional correspondence or materials regarding Wayne County's noncompliance with Standard 5, compliance with which was mandated by April 2022. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Annika Brigham" 
The request has been granted in part and denied in part. See comments below. 

Comments: 

As to the partial denial, LARA certifies that, to the best of the LARA’s knowledge, information, and belief, the records/information requested [final FY24 compliance plan] do not exist within LARA under the description given or another reasonably known to LARA.  MCL 15.235(5)(b). Included is the draft compliance plan. This plan is not final until reviewed and approved by the Commission. 
Additionally, the records/information you requested have been redacted because they contain information of a personal nature [personal telephone number] that, if disclosed, would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of an individual’s privacy and financial information that would identify, or provide a means of identifying, a person that may, as a result of the disclosure of the information, become a victim of a cybersecurity incident. MCL 15.243(1)(a) and (z). 
The records are available in the . (https://u8387778.ct.sendgrid.net/ls/click?upn=6HtRfOYLt5fXvpttM-2FU1HRRDUyJKMck8CnS5-2FT3nJ2fROqV-2FDqw20Wu4P-2BXhrWui6GnhdL0-2Fn0BK6vWJb-2F4IG5AhyOaoOssSAc4mKSr29mc-3D5AK__-2BbsKRAAXh5AeXozRhSigurriW-2FVS0CE0t-2BEa1u2J0pdSfndJ6oWcjNhIgu5BmKgVTSB3PlBbt8NpKHZXVmKgY435q9MwITQK2dBWv2-2BPjpxbKe2jgWWxdHLTZGyQxo0RkblRYNDCpXbairaCMnScKdBFdb-2FRZajZRF1cEG093Fv7AzMqtT1-2FLnh7wRpyZmAKktT2ocVh5UZAO4iXrF7HiTxnCz4xBZM1tAWbOwMmFqYtvXMKbM22ogLXaL4fzMxegsV4Basy0KemiFNidTxM2pVSt-2Fs73-2FAXmUtb46Mi1u4qc8oO4cC-2B0j6dPxKPlgJ09U-2FSfSEVwbZf3jTdRG-2FZRlVl075XRuWIag2Kvh9c8uJ5kqOerHU7nWPo0oHeMPqz-2FKI6bO7zTzJscsG6-2FaapMQ-3D-3D) FOIA Center 
Please note: these records will be available in the FOIA Center for 365 calendar days and will then be destroyed as required by the Department’s records and retention schedule. Under section 10 of the FOIA, MCL 15.240, the Department is obligated to inform you that you may do the following: 

1)  Appeal this decision in writing to Appeals Officer Adam Sandoval, Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs, P.O. Box 30004, Lansing, MI 48909.  The writing must specifically state the word “appeal” and must identify the reason or reasons you believe the partial denial should be reversed.  The head of the Department or her designee must respond to your appeal within 10 business days of its receipt.  Under unusual circumstances, the time for response to your appeal may be extended by 10 business days. 

2)  Commence an action in the Court of Claims within 180 days after the date of the final determination to deny the request.  If you prevail in such an action, the court is to award reasonable attorney fees, costs, and disbursements, and possible damages. 
If you have questions concerning this matter, please email us at . (mailto:larafoiainfo@michigan.gov) larafoiainfo@michigan.gov 
To review a copy of LARA’s written public summary, procedures, and guidelines, please visit . communications.subject: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: DHS WI
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

According to the USDA, in 2022, DHS was awarded $741,751 by the USDA through their SNAP Fraud Framework Implementation Grant to develop a data analysis program that will "quickly identify and analyze fraudulent SNAP transactions, identify fraud trends, and allow data and data analysis to be readily accessible to data analysts and investigators in all stages of the investigation."

I am seeking:

1) Contracts, memorandums of understanding, and statements of work between the department and any outside party regarding the implementation of any service to detect or predict fraud

2) Documentation of all decision-making algorithms, fraud detection,, or predictive models pursuant to this grant or that the agency currently uses (including those used as aids to human decision making). This documentation should include, where available: executive summaries of the algorithm/model's purpose, lists of the data sources, breakdowns of how the model weights various input data, descriptions of the statistical or machine learning techniques employed, the results of validation and accuracy testing, disparate impact studies, and algorithmic impact reports.

3) A data dictionary/library for each predictive or detection model or algorithm identified in response to items 1 and 2 of this requests.

4) Copies of any internal or independent audits of the identified models or algorithms.

5) Aggregate or disaggregated data, if any exists, breaking down the risk scores or outputs of the fraud model.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Dhruv Mehrotra

communications.subject: FW: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: DHS WI
communications.communication:
This email is to acknowledge your request to the Department of Health Services (DHS) regarding the SNAP Fraud Framework Implementation Grant.  As the custodian of this record, DHS has asked the Office of the Inspector General (OIG) to respond. We are in the process of analyzing the request.

OIG gives public records requests high priority and provides requested records as soon as practicable and without delay. A reasonable time for response to a specific public record request depends on the nature of the request, the staff and other resources available to process the request, the extent of the request, and whether confidential material contained in the responsive records must be redacted.

According to Wis. Stat. § 19.35(3), the Department may charge for locating records if the cost is $50 or more, as well as the costs of copies or scanning and mailing/shipping the records responsive to the request. We will prepare an estimate for the cost of the requested documents, if any, and will submit an invoice to you before compiling the records. Also, under Wis. Stat. § 19.35(3)(f), OIG will require prepayment of the estimated cost of providing a copy of the records to you if the total cost exceeds $5.

You may direct any questions concerning this request to dhsoigopenrecordsrequest@wi.gov<mailto:dhsoigopenrecordsrequest@wi.gov>.

Sincerely,

Anthony J. Baize
Inspector General
Wisconsin Department of Health Services
Phone: 608.266.2521
Fax: 608.267.3380

communications.subject: RE: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: DHS WI
communications.communication:
This email is to follow-up on your request to the Department of Health Services (DHS) Office of the Inspector General (OIG)  regarding the SNAP Fraud Framework Implementation Grant. You have requested:

1) Contracts, memorandums of understanding, and statements of work between the department and any outside party regarding the implementation of any service to detect or predict fraud Responsive records are attached. "ebtINSIGHT Amendment" & "IVR-Common Pin Amendment"
2) Documentation of all decision-making algorithms, fraud detection,, or predictive models pursuant to this grant or that the agency currently uses (including those used as aids to human decision making). This documentation should include, where available: executive summaries of the algorithm/model's purpose, lists of the data sources, breakdowns of how the model weights various input data, descriptions of the statistical or machine learning techniques employed, the results of validation and accuracy testing, disparate impact studies, and algorithmic impact reports. We are working to identify and redact trade secrets and will provide a redacted copy as soon as practicable.
3) A data dictionary/library for each predictive or detection model or algorithm identified in response to items 1 and 2 of this requests. There are no responsive records.
4) Copies of any internal or independent audits of the identified models or algorithms. There are no responsive records.
5) Aggregate or disaggregated data, if any exists, breaking down the risk scores or outputs of the fraud model. There are no responsive records.

Wisconsin open records statutes specifically exclude from release "any record or portion of a record containing information qualifying as a trade secret". (Wis. Stat. § 19.36 (5)).

If you believe that the Department has improperly determined that materials should not be provided to you, please do not hesitate to contact me. Further, if you do so believe, you have a right under Wis. Stat. § 19.37(1)  to have the determination reviewed by mandamus or upon application to the attorney general or appropriate district attorney.

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any investigative reports for false reports of active shootings or bomb threats called into to establishments in Kenosha, Somers, or anywhere that Kinshasa PD provides services to since January 1 2022.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Dhruv Mehrotra

communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Dhruv Mehrotra,

I am in receipt of your Public Records Request sent to the Kenosha Police Department (KPD). I am the custodian of records for KPD which include our responses for service calls within the city of Kenosha.  

Your request is attached for reference.  Could you please be more specific to the records you are seeking when citing: "any investigative reports for false reports of active shootings or bomb threats."  KPD responds to hundreds of shots fired calls that are unfounded.  Are you looking "swatting prank" calls that would include reported calls of mass shootings or bomb threats to schools or businesses or of a specific incident(s)

Please feel free to contact me via email or by phone so that I may address the records requests to your satisfaction.

Respectfully,

Sgt. Galley
Office of Professional Standards.
262-605-5147

communications.subject: Reference No: 2020-IGFO-00030
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,

The Department of Homeland Security (DHS), Office of Inspector General (OIG) is currently working on our backlog of FOIAs.

We apologize for the delay in response as we have been working through a backlog of cases. We are reaching out to you to check if you're still interested in this case.

Please indicate Yes or No your continued interest in pursuing these records within 30 calendar days from the date of this email.

Because the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) is currently in a telework status due to the outbreak of COVID-19 you may notify us in writing via email at foia.oig@oig.dhs.gov<mailto:foia.oig@oig.dhs.gov>.

If we do not receive a response within 30 days, we will assume you are no longer interested in this FOIA request and will administratively close this case.

Should you have any questions about this response, please contact us via email at foia.oig@oig.dhs.gov<mailto:foia.oig@oig.dhs.gov>.


Sincerely,

DHS-OIG FOIA Team

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: FOIL: Schenectady City School District and Common Thread Consulting, LLC
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all cash receipts, invoices, and work product produced by Common Thread Consulting, LLC, a limited liability company owned by Schenectady City Councilman Damonni Farley, for services provided to the Schenectady City School District from January 1, 2015 to July 1, 2021. This includes but is not limited to:

Invoices or billing statements submitted by Common Thread Consulting, LLC to the Schenectady City School District.
Cash receipts showing payment by the Schenectady City School District to Common Thread Consulting, LLC.
Work product produced by Common Thread Consulting, LLC for the Schenectady City School District, including any reports, presentations, or other documents.
Any communications between Schenectady City School District employees and Common Thread Consulting, LLC regarding the services provided by the company.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jackson Parker

title: Use of force (response to resistance) guidance, policies, and data (Metropolitan Police Department)

communications.subject: DC Freedom of Information Act Request: Use of force (response to resistance) guidance, policies, and data (Metropolitan Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the DC Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records related to this agency's policies on and reporting of uses of force and responses to resistance:

• Policies. 
Any and all policies guiding appropriate and inappropriate uses of force by any member or representative of this agency. These may also include “Response to Resistance” policies and similar guidance.

Please also provide all policies regarding the use of lethal, less-lethal, and non-lethal weapons (for example: TASERs pepper ball guns, rubber bullets, gases, sprays, water, etc.), including all policies regarding borrowing, accessing, or assuming responsibility for such weapons,  tools, and ammunition. 

Please also provide all policies or guidance related to reporting or tracking discharges from or uses of such weapons, as well as any other applicable policies or directives related to the acquisition, use, and reporting of weapons or tools. 

Please also provide all policies and guidance used to evaluate any use of force or adjudicate administrative and internal investigations into any use of force or weapon discharge.

• Instructions for reporting. Any and all instructions and guidance related to the reporting of uses of force by any member or representative of this agency.

• Forms, coding descriptions, and other guidance.
All forms, codes, guides, and guidance used in the reporting and review of uses of force or weapons, including:
Any list of codes or definitions for terms or tags used in the reporting, collection, or review of uses of force. 
A blank version of each form, log, and other documentation used to report or track uses of force by this agency.  
A blank version of each form, log, and other documentation used to report or track the borrowing or use of lethal, less-lethal, and non-lethal weapons
A blank version of each form, log, and other documentation used to report or track any discharge of force from firearms, tools, or weapons employed by this agency
A copy of any guidance, requirements, laws, and policies issued by the state, including those issued as part of grant or other funding requirements, regarding this agency’s responsibilities for reportings uses of force or weapons
A copy of any guidance, requirements, laws, and policies issued by the federal government, including those issued as part of grant or other funding requirements, regarding this agency’s responsibilities for reportings uses of force or weapons

• Use of Force Data 
For the period from January 1, 2019 through December 31, 2019 and the period from January 1, 2020 through July 31, 2020, data on the each use of force by representatives of this agency, including but not limited to: 
Date, time: The date (month, day, year) and time of the incident
Location: Street address, block, and other relevant location information
Subject(s) information: race, ethnicity, national origin, age, gender, resultant or related injuries sustained or alleged, weapon type (if applicable) in the possession of each involved individual, arrests or charges associated with the incident
Officer information (for each involved officer): employee number or other unique identifier used for the officer, race, resultant or related physical injuries, patrol division, unit
Incident details: incident or other unique identification number for the use of force incident
Type of force details: a description of each type of force used
Body camera or other footage: Inventory of any video record was created of the incident and/or a copy of the captured footage from all present cameras
Disposition of investigation into the incident: The current or final status of each use of force incident, including whether challenges to the use of force were sustained or dismissed or if the incident had no or is currently under investigation
Please provide the information as a csv spreadsheet, if possible, and if not possible, please provide incident reports sufficient to show the requested data. 

• Discharge Report Data 
For the period from January 1, 2019 through December 31, 2019 and the period from January 1, 2020 through July 31, 2020, data on each discharge of a firearm and other weapons by representatives of this agency, including but not limited to: 
Date, time: The date (month, day, year) and time of the incident
Location: Street address, block, and other relevant location information
Incident description and details
Tool or weapon used, including any unique identifier or identification number
Number of discharges
Subject(s) information: race, ethnicity, national origin, age, gender, resultant or related injuries sustained or alleged, weapon type (if applicable) in the possession of each involved individual, arrests or charges associated with the incident
Officer information (for each involved officer): employee number or other unique identifier used for the officer, race, resultant or related physical injuries, patrol division, unit
Type of force details: a description of each type of force used
Disposition or status of any investigation or follow-up review of the incident
Please provide the information as a csv spreadsheet, if possible, and if not possible, please provide incident reports sufficient to show the requested data. 

If any portion of materials responsive to this request should be deemed unavailable or non-disclosable, please specifically identify the portions of the records or the specific information that is unavailable and the reason for the unavailability. 

If any portion of this request is unclear or if this request could be modified to reduce the burden of producing responsive documents or provide them more efficiently or expeditiously, please reply with a request for clarification or a proposed modification.

This request is being made by a reporter as part of a journalistic investigation. It is being submitted as part of a project to better understand uses of police force nationwide, which has been of public interest for many years and which is of particular interest to large new swaths of the public following the widely-seen death of George Floyd and the First Amendment-protected demonstrations and public discussion that have followed. 

In the event that there are fees appropriately assessed in association with this request, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.

I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Pennsylvania Right to Know Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. A summary of traffic stops made by Pittsburgh Police between 1/1/23 and 3/31/23. Please provide these in the same format as my previous request: 129-01-2023.

3. Any additional training materials or documentation for how this data is created or how it should be used internally.

If any part of this request is denied, please move forward with the remainder of the request and cite the relevant provisions in state law which justify the denial.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Josh Chamberlain

communications.subject: RE: Pennsylvania Right to Know Act Request: Q1 2023 Traffic Stops
communications.communication:
Hi Ms. Hotham,

Thank you for this document. It meets part of the request, but there are some issues:

1. It is missing some properties which were present on the previous document: STOP_ID, REPORT_ID, NBR_OF_OCCUP, FINDING_NA, PERSON_ID, CENSUS, and NEIGHBORHOOD. Can you explain why these would be omitted?

2. I requested a data dictionary describing the properties present in the table, and how they relate to other records. Is there no such document which describes these properties? For example, how would someone know what "FINDING_NA" means, or "REPORT_ID"?

3. I requested any additional training materials or documentation for how this data is created or how it should be used internally. Are there no documents related to training officers to collect data during traffic stops?

Thank you.

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to request information pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), 5 U.S.C. § 552. Specifically, I am seeking access to the following information regarding migrant remains that have been documented in your Medical Examiner Officer or County Sheriff's files for fiscal years 2017 - 2022:

Age
Sex
Body condition
Coordinates where the body was located
Country of origin
Cause of death

I understand that these records may contain sensitive information, and I assure you that any information provided will be used solely for legitimate research purposes.

Please inform me of any fees associated with this request, and I would be happy to provide payment if necessary. Additionally, please let me know if there are any limitations on the amount of information that can be provided, or if you require any further information from me in order to process this request.

Sincerely,

Gabriela Villegas
